  <!--</div>-->
  <p>According to data from the Centro de Estudios Economicos del Sector de la Construccion (Construction Sector’s Economic Resarch Centre,
    known as CEESCO by its Spanish Acronym), annual growth for the construction industry is expected to be around 1.0% - 2.0% by the end of 2018,
    expecting a slowdown in growth derived from the Federal government transition and the halt of some infrastructure projects. Among the challenges
    to be faced in the following years are investment levels, the greater efficiency in the allocation of public resources and the creation of new
    financing mechanisms.</p>

  <p>The upward trend in the construction sector's costs continues, accumulating an inflation of 10.5% YoY as of September, with building materials 
    showing the steepest increases, registering double-digit annual growth rates in steel rods (+33.1%), wire products (+31.0%) and steel mesh (+24.2%).
    For the industry, an inflation above 12.0% YoY is expected for the end of the year, as the steel duties imposed by Mexico to the US is not removed
    in the new trilateral agreement.</p>


